SVX0RUgrFg45HozhdtzLwygubxcojeV%2FxxMchR6EQBY21VTLG4wiTOaCq5PSKDuY8vyo4ln68OKdwzOB%2B1wXcSErhxszWJYUr%2Bg%2BN1K9U%2Bnixlds%2FEnu3P8MfZKpKJq5sHM5xeD%2BHykuUKiJVGM0cxCyoRDqOvHehGcSZhAeiHuFG4KS8Z%2FqiT0BFq7gcrjL2OM6229ub6XUpq16e7Jb64f1KZW692Hig9OH2qpzHU2FJdcG5y4%2FFO6ookf66FIjHB%2FX%2FUfxo4V737%2Fp4LE6HS7hF4I6%2BaJKKNsw%2F%2BsR4u23Y06IFP%2F94%2BgOeOiUZz83mjC90%2BFwWx8w353t%2B6j5UXo0%2BvP9wvz9TJ%2FaY0ofxorgfxcOaIQt9X1e6bUUJekVZ%2BoyfPf8P92sDLA%3D%3D" id="w1_2_3_5_7_9_18"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="2603" y="1775" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+5+7+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   64k lives-eq/$1k · 61% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 39%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + nature_intrinsic_value + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + animals_matter_a_lot + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 nature_intrinsic_value → 5 future_humans_matter_w